Thanks to @Koala Yeung, I have formed an answer. Koala said that because the click event does not carry a keycode, my function was not running. So I removed the line ```if (e.keyCode == 13{}``` however, it was still not running the function. So I did some research on bug checking. And one good way I found is to place ```console.log(&#39;&#39;);``` in places where a function or an if/else statement might be ran. My original function then looked like this:
```
// watch button for click
             $(&#39;#sendbutton&#39;).click(function(e) {  

                    console.log(&quot;it got this far at least&quot;);
                  
                    var text = $(self).val();
                    var maxLength = $(self).attr(&quot;maxlength&quot;);  
                    var length = text.length; 
                     
                    // send 
                    if (length &lt;= maxLength + 1) { 
                        
                        console.log(&quot;passed maxlenght test&quot;);

                        chat.send(text, name);
                        console.log(&#39;message was sent by Pressing Send. Message: &#39; + text + &quot; Length: &quot; + length + &quot;.&quot;); 
                        //clears the textarea after send
                        $(self).val(&quot;&quot;);
                        
                    } else {
                        console.log(&#39;did not pass maxlength test&#39;)
                        $(self).val(text.substring(0, maxLength));
                    }   
    
             });
```
Then if I got ```it got this far at least``` then I would know it received the button press. After that, I got the string ```did not pass maxlength test``` which means it ran the else after the if statement, even though I wanted it to run the if statement itself. That&#39;s about when I realized that it was trying to check the maxlegth of the self property. But a button doesn&#39;t have a maxlength attribute! So I replaced all of the self properties with ```&#39;#sendie&#39;``` and It worked! It actually worked. And that is rare for my javascript &#39;skill&#39;. And that is also good for bug checking. I learned something today. And I am so gratefull for it too.

